The '''''San Giorgio'' class''' consisted of two [[armored cruiser]]s built for the Royal Italian Navy (''[[Regia Marina]]'') in the first decade of the 20th century. The second ship, {{ship|Italian cruiser|San Marco||2}}, was used to evaluate recently invented [[steam turbine]]s in a large ship and incorporated a number of other technological advances. The ships participated in the [[Italo-Turkish War]] of 1911–12, although {{ship|Italian cruiser|San Giorgio||2}} was under repair for most of the war. ''San Marco'' supported ground forces in [[Libya]] with [[Naval gunfire support|naval gunfire]] and helped them to occupy towns in Libya and islands in the [[Dodecanese]]. During World War I, the ships' activities were limited by the threat of [[Austro-Hungarian]] submarines, although they did [[Battle of Durazzo (1918)|bombard Durazzo, Albania]] in 1918.

''San Giorgio'' spent several years in the Far East and Italian Somaliland after the war and became a [[training ship]] in 1931. After a brief deployment to Spain in 1936, she was reconstructed to better serve her role as a training ship. The ship's [[anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft armament]] was augmented when she was deployed to [[Tobruk]], Libya to reinforce the port's defenses after Italy declared war on Britain in May 1940. ''San Giorgio'' was [[scuttled]] in early 1941 when Allied forces were poised to capture the port. Her wreck was [[Marine salvage|salvaged]] in 1952, but sank while under tow. ''San Marcos'' was converted into a [[target ship]] in the early 1930s and was found sunk at the end of the war. She was [[ship breaking|scrapped]] in 1949.

==Design and description==
[[File:San Giorgio Brasseys 1912.jpg|thumb|left|Right elevation and deck plan from [[Brassey's Naval Annual]] 1912]]
The ''San Giorgio'' class was ordered almost immediately after the preceding {{sclass-|Pisa|cruiser|0}} ships, and was an improved version of that design. The [[forecastle]] was extended to improve seaworthiness, [[gun turret|turret]] armor was increased, habitability was improved and the propulsion machinery was redistributed. ''San Marco'' was given the first steam turbines fitted in a large Italian ship for comparative purposes with ''San Giorgio'', which retained the traditional [[Marine steam engine#Triple or multiple expansion|vertical triple-expansion steam engines]] (VTE). ''San Marco'' was a very innovative ship as she was the first turbine-powered ship in any navy to have four [[propeller shaft]]s, the first with a [[gyroscopic compass]], the first with [[antiroll tanks]], and the first not to use wood in any way.<ref>Gardiner & Gray, pp. 252, 261</ref>

The ''San Giorgio''-class ships had a [[length between perpendiculars]] of {{convert|131.04|m|ftin|sp=us}} and an [[length overall|overall length]] of {{convert|140.89|m|ftin|sp=us}}. They had a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|21.03|m|ftin|sp=us}} and a [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|7.35|-|7.76|m|ftin|sp=us}}. The ships displaced {{convert|10167|-|10969|t|LT|sp=us}} at normal load, and {{convert|11300|-|11900|t|LT|sp=us}} at [[deep load]]. The ships had a complement of 32 officers and 666 to 673 enlisted men.<ref name=f8>Fraccaroli, p. 33</ref>

===Propulsion===
The machinery installation of this class was changed in comparison to that of the ''Pisa'' class, with the engines [[amidships]] with the 14 mixed-firing [[water-tube boiler]]s fore and aft of the engines. Their exhausts were trunked together into two widely spaced pairs of [[funnel (ship)|funnel]]s. Designed for a maximum speed of {{convert|23|kn|lk=in}},<ref name=s8>Silverstone, p. 290</ref> the two ships were given different types of propulsion machinery for evaluation. ''San Giorgio''{{'}}s two shafts, pair of {{convert|19500|ihp|lk=in
adj=on}} VTE steam engines and [[Blechynden boiler]]s differed only slightly from those used by the ''Pisa''s. In contrast, ''San Marco''{{'}}s four shafts, each driven by a license-built [[Parsons Marine Steam Turbine Company|Parsons]] steam turbine, was a first for the ''Regia Marina''. The turbines used steam provided by [[Babcock & Wilcox boiler]]s at a working pressure of {{convert|210|psi|kPa kg/cm2|0|abbr=on|lk=on}}<ref name=a7>Attilio, p. 477</ref> to reach their designed output of {{convert|23000|shp|abbr=on}}. Both ships exceeded their designed speeds, with ''San Giorgio'' reaching {{convert|23.2|kn}} and ''San Marco'' {{convert|23.75|kn}} during their [[sea trial]]s. The biggest difference between the sisters was that the turbines of ''San Marco'' proved to be significantly less economical in service (a range of {{convert|4800|nmi|lk=in}} at a speed of {{convert|10|kn}} and {{convert|2480|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|21.25|kn}}) compared to ''San Giorgio''{{'}}s VTE steam engines ({{convert|6270|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|10|kn}} and {{convert|2640|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|21.25|kn}}.<ref name=g0>Gardiner & Gray, p. 261</ref>

===Armament===
The main armament of the ''San Giorgio''-class ships consisted of four [[EOC 10-inch /45 naval gun|Cannone da 254/45 A Modello 1907]]<ref group=Note>The ''/45'' denotes the length of the gun barrels; in this case, the gun is 45 [[Calibers#Caliber as measurement of length|caliber]], meaning that the gun is 45 times long as it is in diameter.</ref> guns in electrically powered, twin-[[gun turret]]s fore and aft of the [[superstructure]].<ref name=g0/> The turrets had an arc of fire of 260°.<ref name=a7/> The {{convert|254|mm|abbr=on}} gun fired {{convert|450|-|500|lb|kg|adj=on|disp=flip|1}} [[armor-piercing shot and shell|armor-piercing (AP)]] projectiles at a [[muzzle velocity]] of {{convert|2850|ft/s|m/s|sp=us|disp=flip}}. At maximum elevation of +25°, the guns had a range of about {{convert|25000|m|yd|sp=us}}.<ref>Campbell, p. 324; Friedman, pp. 68, 238</ref> The ships mounted eight [[Cannone da 190/45 A Modello 1908]] in four electrically powered twin-gun turrets, two in each side amidships, as their secondary armament. Their arc of fire was 160°.<ref name=a7/> These [[Armstrong Whitworth]] {{convert|190|mm|abbr=on}} guns fired
{{convert|90.9|kg|adj=on}} AP shells at {{convert|2835|-|2927|ft/s|m/s|disp=flip|abbr=on}}. At maximum elevation of +25°, the guns had a range of about {{convert|22000|m|yd|sp=us}}.<ref>Campbell, p. 329; Friedman, pp. 79, 239</ref>

For defense against [[torpedo boat]]s, the ''San Giorgio''s mounted 18 [[List of British ordnance terms#QF|quick-firing (QF)]] 40-caliber {{convert|76|mm|abbr=on}} guns. Eight of these were mounted in [[embrasure]]s in the sides of the hull and the rest in the superstructure.<ref name=g0/> The ships were also fitted with a pair of QF 40-caliber {{convert|47|mm|abbr=on}} guns. The ''San Giorgio''-class ships were equipped with three submerged {{convert|450|mm|in|abbr=on|1}} [[torpedo tube]]s. During World War I, eight of the 76&nbsp;mm guns were replaced by six 76&nbsp;mm [[anti-aircraft gun|anti-aircraft (AA) guns]]<ref name=g0/> and one torpedo tube was removed.<ref name=s8/>

===Protection===
The ships were protected by an [[belt armor|armored belt]] that was {{convert|200|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} thick amidships and reduced to {{convert|80|mm|abbr=on|1}} at the bow and stern.<ref name=s8/> The belt was {{convert|7|ft|3|in|m|1|disp=flip|abbr=on}} high, of which {{convert|4|ft|11|in|m|1|disp=flip|abbr=on}} was below the [[waterline]].<ref name=a7/> The armored [[deck (ship)|deck]] was {{convert|50|mm|abbr=on}} thick and the [[conning tower]] armor was 254&nbsp;mm thick. The 254&nbsp;mm gun turrets were protected by 200&nbsp;mm of armour while the 190&nbsp;mm turrets had {{convert|160|mm|abbr=on|1}}.<ref name=g0/>

