==Service==
[[File:RN San Giorgio (1908) stranded 1913.jpg|thumb|left|''San Giorgio'' aground in 1913]]
''San Giorgio'' [[Ship grounding|ran aground]] in August 1911 off [[Naples]]-[[Posillipo]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000206/19110909/090/0006|title=Stranded Italian Cruiser|date=9 September 1911|work=Manchester Courier and Lancashire General Advertiser|page=6|accessdate=28 February 2015| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> heavily damaged, she was under repair until June 1912, missing most of the Italo-Turkish War. ''San Marco'' supported the occupations of [[Benghazi]] and [[Derna, Libya]] during the war and bombarded the fortifications defending the entrance to the [[Dardanelles]].<ref>Beehler, pp. 30, 49, 84; Stephenson, pp. 217, 262–65</ref> She also supported the forces occupying the island of [[Rhodes]] in May 1912. In February 1913, ''San Giorgio'' cruised the [[Aegean Sea]] and made a port visit to [[Salonica]], Greece, the next month.<ref>Marchese</ref> She ran aground again on 21 November in the [[Strait of Messina]], but was only slightly damaged.<ref name=s5/>

During World War I, the activities of the ships were restricted by the threat of submarine attack after the armored cruisers {{ship|Italian cruiser|Giuseppe Garibaldi|1899|2}} and {{ship|Italian cruiser|Amalfi||2}} were sunk by submarines shortly after Italy joined the war in May 1915, although the ships did participate in the bombardment of Durazzo, Albania in late 1918.<ref>Halpern, pp. 148, 151, 176; Sondhaus, p. 289</ref>

After the war, ''San Giorgio'' was deployed to the [[Far East]]<ref name=s6/> while ''San Marcos'' played a minor role in the [[Corfu incident]] in 1923.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000687/19230922/295/0009|title=Greek Reparations: Evacuation of Corfu Begun|date=22 September 1923|work=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer|page=9|accessdate=1 March 2015| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|subscription=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000320/19231001/040/0002|title=Italy and Greece: Indemnity Paid Over|date=1 October 1923|work=Gloucestershire Echo|page=2|accessdate=1 March 2015| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|subscription=yes}}</ref> ''San Giorgio'', escorted by ''San Marco'', ferried [[Crown Prince]] [[Umberto II of Italy|Umberto]] to South America in July–September 1924,<ref>{{cite news|title=Prince Humbert Sails|date=2 July 1924|work=The New York Times|page=31|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Humbert Sails Home from Brazil|date=20 September 1924|work=The New York Times|page=22|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref> and then supported operations in [[Italian Somaliland]] in 1925–26.<ref name=s6/> The ship was disarmed and converted into a radio-controlled target ship in 1931–35; her old boilers were replaced by four oil-burning ones which reduced her maximum speed to {{convert|18|kn}}. She was captured by the Germans when they occupied [[La Spezia]] on 9 September 1943; ''San Marcos'' was found at the end of the war half-sunk in the harbor there and was broken up in 1949.<ref name=g2/>

From 1930 to 1935, ''San Giorgio'' was based in [[Pula|Pola]] as a training ship, and was sent to Spain after the [[Spanish Civil War]] began in 1936 to protect Italian interests.<ref name=s6>Sicurezza, p. 46</ref> In 1937–38 she was reconstructed to serve as a dedicated training ship for [[naval cadet]]s at the [[Arsenale di La Spezia]]: six boilers were removed and the remaining eight were converted to burn fuel oil which reduced her speed to {{convert|16|-|17|kn}}. Each pair of funnels was trunked together and her 76/40 guns were replaced by 47-caliber {{convert|100|mm|abbr=on|1}} guns in four twin turrets abreast the funnels. Her torpedo tubes were also removed while she received a light AA suite for the first time, with the addition of six 54-caliber Breda {{convert|37|mm|abbr=on}} guns, a dozen {{convert|20|mm|abbr=on}} [[Breda Model 35]] autocannon and four {{convert|13.2|mm|abbr=on}} [[Breda Model 31]] machine guns in two twin mounts.<ref name=g2/><ref name=b4>Brescia, p. 104</ref>

[[File:Italian cruiser San Giorgio scuttled at Tobruk 1941.jpg|thumb|left|Aerial view of ''San Giorgio'' on fire after being scuttled]] 
Prior to her being sent to reinforce the defenses of Tobruk in early May 1940, a fifth 100/47 gun turret was added on the forecastle and five more twin 13.2&nbsp;mm machine gun mounts were added to better suit her new role as a floating battery.<ref name=b4/> Two days after Italy declared war on Britain on 10 June, the British [[light cruiser]]s {{HMS|Gloucester|62|2}} and {{HMS|Southampton|83|2}} bombarded Tobruk and attacked ''San Giorgio'', which was not hit during the engagement.<ref>Rohwer, p. 28</ref> A British submarine fired two torpedoes at ''San Giorgio'' on 19 June, but these detonated before reaching the ship.<ref>[http://uboat.net/allies/warships/ship/3400.html "HMS Parthian (N 75)"]. ''uboat.net''. Retrieved 2 March 2015.</ref> The ship's guns engaged [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] aircraft attacking Tobruk many times, destroying several. She was scuttled in shallow water on 22 January 1941 to prevent her capture during the [[Battle of Tobruk (1941)|Battle of Tobruk]].<ref name=b4/> ''San Giorgio'' was awarded the [[Gold Medal of Military Valour]] (''Medaglia d'Oro al Valore Militare'') for her performance at Tobruk.<ref>San Giorgio</ref> Her wreck was refloated in 1952, but sank under tow en route to Italy.<ref name=b4/>

